<br>
Second:  Damage/Mana is not the only issue.<br>
<br>
Damage/Time is a separate issue when it comes to buffs, pets, and damage shields(and to a lesser extent, DoT's).<br>
<br>
For nukes, it is all directly connected.  Nuke damage done over time is directly related to your mana regeneration.  Buffs have the limiting factor in that they cannot stack.  If all that mattered was damage/mana, we could cast Cadeau 10 times in a row so that the tank would have 330pt damage shield.<br>
<br>
In normal situations, you'll likely med back the mana you spend on damage shields in a fairly short amount of time, meaning that you must find a use for that mana or &quot;sin against Karana&quot;<br>
<br>
Remember also, that not only does Cadeau have a duration, Cadeau is dependant <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  both</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on being in battle and it is dependant on the number of hits from the mob in order to do it's damage.  The power of haste, while limited by duration and time-in-combat exactly like a damage shield, is multiplied by the number of tanks you cast it on.  Cadeau is capped by the offensive ability of the mob, and one does not get a multiple effect if cast on multiple targets.  One would only use a DS on multiple targets as a precaution.<br>
<br>
Also, buffs can be dispelled, but that's an issue for another time.<br>
<br>
Pets also, are dependant on several things to deal damage.  Pets, unlike haste and damage shields, are not limited by duration, except for the risk that they can be killed.  Otherwise, pets work similarly in that their damage/time suffers when there are long periods of downtime.  However, during those situations the damage/time of nukes remains constant.<br>
<br>
What it comes down to is that pets, nukes, and damage shields are three entirely different methods of dealing damage, so much so that a simple damage/mana comparison is not an adequete measure of their value.<br>
<br>
Consider the value of nukes to eliminate a mob quickly.   Spend your nuking mana on mobs with high <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  offensive</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> ability.  By only nuking the mobs with the most powerful melee or most dangerous spells, you will save your cleric mana and occaisionally even prevent a wipeout.  The high hp mobs are the ones where you train your pet and damage shields upon them.  If a high HP mob has a low offense, it is best to save your nukes and let your pet and the melees maximize their potential.  Usually, high HP and high offense tend to coincide, however this is not a hard and fast rule.  The dangerously offensive mobs are the ones you want to spend your mana on, or possibly on the dangerously defensive mobs(clerics, gaters).  Although if you're facing a cleric that continually heals himself, the best strategy, if you cannot kill the cleric mid-cast, is to maximize your mana effeciency through the pet and damage shields.<br>
<br>
