 BOLD END-->  If all that mattered was damage/mana, we could cast Cadeau 10 times in a row so that the tank would have 330pt damage shield.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Assuming enemy attention is focused on a Main Tank, only the first Cadeau yields a high DPM.  All others add nothing, and so yield 0 DPM.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Goladus:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Cadeau is dependant both on being in battle and it is dependant on the number of hits from the mob in order to do it's damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->My original analysis, referenced in the first message in this thread, addresses this, and lays out my other assumptions.  I discussed the raid situation I was most familiar with, continuous pulls at Kael Arena, with occasional pops and adds, with most but not all attention focused on a single Main Tank.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Goladus:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  What it comes down to is that pets, nukes, and damage shields are three entirely different methods of dealing damage, so much so that a simple damage/mana comparison is not an adequete measure of their value.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, but I think a more sophisticated analysis could yield useful comparisons.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rhion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  I never said you should nuke high HP mobs. Where the heck did you get that from?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Razamatazz:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Too much information, too many quotes and references.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rhion:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> Very terse, almost no quotes or references.<br>
<br>
I am sorry, Rhion, I am not sure what you are talking about here.  I do think that comparing things to nukes is a useful first approximation, at least in ordinary circumstances.  After all, if our nukes are worthless, what are we doing here?  In theory, nukes make the enemy stop doing bad things earlier, and therefore have some value.  I am not suggesting nuking, just using nukes for comparision, as they are relatively simple to analyze.  They are the caster equivalent of damage/delay.<br>
<br>
On the other hand, I have certainly not fought the high end mobs in long fights, as you have.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Goladus:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> If you use Malosi, you can't accurately judge the damage you might be doing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Actually, this is one of the things one could reliably measure with log files of controlled fights, i.e. fight the same mobs with or without Malosi, and count the number of resists.<br>
<br>
I can also use DPM to analyze it.  For example, suppose I am casually soloing blue fire resistant mobs in SkyFire, studying XML while I med between fights.  Suppose I pull with Malosi and cast Shock of Steel three times per mob.  Further, assume Gobaner is marginally mana free: i.e., he never dies, and I use right-clicks to BO3 and DS him.<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 175 Mana Malosi + 3 * 275 Mana Shock of Steel = 1000 Mana
795 damage * 3 unresisted Shocks of Steel = 2385 damage / 1000 mana = 2.385 DPM</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END-->Which is either marginal or adequate, depending on your point of view.  If I skip Malosi entirely, pull with Shock, and am resisted one third of the time, I get:<!--EZCODE CODE START--><pre> 1590 damage / 825 mana = 1.93 DPM</pre><!--EZCODE CODE END--><br>
This is my starting analysis, and if I wish, I can collect logs to check my real resist rates with and without Malosi and plug those numbers in.  Clearly, as the number of nukes per mob increases, Maliso becomes more efficient.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NOTE:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> I am NOT suggesting that the above tactics are optimal, but merely for the sake of discussing how Malosi could be analyzed and measured.<br>
<br>
